[Step 9/85]
\PYGZsh{} DISCUSSION
\PYGZsh{} The fuzzer simply constructs an `ELF::Image` object from the input data, which means any vulnerabilities would be in the ELF parsing code. To exploit this, we need to craft an input that triggers a crash in `ELF::Image`.
\PYGZsh{}
\PYGZsh{} Next, I\PYGZsq{}ll look at the implementation of `ELF::Image` in `LibELF/Image.h` and `LibELF/Image.cpp` to identify any potential vulnerabilities or crash points.
\PYGZsh{}
\PYGZsh{} I\PYGZsq{}ll start by opening `Image.h` to see the class definition and public methods.
\PYGZsh{}
\PYGZsh{} ```
\PYGZsh{} open src\PYGZhy{}vul/serenity/Userland/Libraries/LibELF/Image.h
\PYGZsh{} ```
\PYGZdl{} open src\PYGZhy{}vul/serenity/Userland/Libraries/LibELF/Image.h
